Hi Shlomi,

[Mormons] Are you sure it is because of their religion and not because of
other factors?
    The cause and effect, of course, can't really be proven either way.  The
founder of the colony in Salt Lake City, Brigham Young, was evidently a
remarkable man, very pragmatic in his outlook, and established the
foundation of what appears to be a very effective culture.

<<It is also possible that Mormons are harmed by religion in other ways.
Like unnecessary guilt, unhappiness, etc.>>
    Oh, the whole, I don't think one can say that, comparing their culture
to those dominated by other religions.  To be sure, they have a certain rate
of defections, but it is fairly low.  Reminds me of something else I asked
about.  In reading a little booklet they gave me, I learned something about
the structure, and there is a "priesthood" with an elaborate structure of
positions to which all male members of the church can aspire.  My niece's
husband is a "high priest", and I learned that her father (my now deceased
brother-in-law) was also one of those.  It sounds to me like almost any
self-respecting Mormon male becomes a high priest.  I asked a woman with
whom I've been acquainted whether there is ever any agitation by women to
have things changed so they can enter the priesthood.  She said only by
defectors from the church.  She said just about all the women take the
attitiude "The men have their role, and we have ours."  And it really seems
to operate that way, with every one contented.  It so happens I'm going to
be going to a convention in Utah in June, and I think I'll ask around among
the various local people I'll be meeting to get a better feel as to how
widespread is membership in the priesthood.

<<<<....sounding like visiting Mormon missionaries. >>
So how is the analogy with Mormon missionaries relevant here?>>
    :-)  That is something I guess you are spared in Israel.  The Mormons
send out many, many missionaries, so many that just about everyone in the US
has had one call at their door.  We used to, but I think after a few visits
they finally got wise that we are unconvertible.  It's a requirement to
belong to the priesthood that one go out "on mission" for a period of time
(maybe six months or a year).  Young women go also (I don't know what the
payoff is for them)  Usually a team of a young man and a young woman,
impeccably dressed (the man in a black suit with a tie), will appear at your
door, act extremely friendly and polite, and if you invite them in, will
give you all the fairy tales and fervently try to persuade you that you will
find a whole new life if you become a True Believer.  Some people try to
keep a lookout so as to not answer their doors when they see Mormon
missionaries approaching.

