    Correct.  A typo.

<<.....their rejection of the Harry Potter series was encouraging...... That
was a funny column.>>
    Good story.  Of course the difference is everyone knows Harry Potter is
intended as fantasty.  There's been an opposite reaction here.  Some
arch-Christian people have protested the Harry Potter thing as teaching kids
to believe in witchcraft.

<<Actually, Sunday in Christianity is not necessarily a Sabbath. A Sabbath
is a day in which no work is necessary to be conducted. Sunday for the
Christians
is a holy day, but for many times, they studied or even worked at it. >>
    Actually, for Christian here, it used to be more of a Sabbath than it is
now.  In studying railroad history, in the mid-to late 19th century, many
railroads would not run trains on Sunday, as a example.  It depended
somewhat on the president of the company, and how devout he was.  And what
are called "blue laws" have persisted, although gradually being attenuated,
until today.  New York State still has a law that alcoholic beverages cannot
be served in restaurants until noon on Sunday.  And liquor stores are not
allowed to be open on Sunday.  But Jews, especially orthodox, certainly do
observe their Sabbath much more consistently than do Christians.

[AE] So now I finally understand why the Jews stick to Saturday.
[SF] Jews don't stick to Saturday as an anti-thesis to Christianity.
Saturday has been the traditional Jewish Sabbath for generations
    I meant that at least partly tongue-in-cheek.  Let's just say that if
some Jews ever had any impulse to shift to Sunday just to conform, the
rationale given by the Christians for that day would be very likely to
dissuade therm.

<<Note that the length of the week was not consistent in the Ancient world.
In Rome, the week was Eight days long. (with a rest day at the end). Jews
 probably followed a different 7-days long week.>>
    I recently researched that.   The weekly cycle in primtive cultures,
evidently, was usually based on the spacing of market days.  In West Africa,
there was a four-day cycle.  In Egypt, ten days.  How the bible happened to
be written to accommodate seven days, it appears, derived from the fact that
ancient Babylonia used seven days.

<<What this book claims (and bases on a lot of evidence) is that until the
late second millenium B.C., men were completely unconscious and operated by
 hallucinating the voices of various gods in their heads and following them.
This is in fact the origin of the conscious religion, which is still present
today. Consciousness in fact nullifies the voices of Gods and enables a
person to control his own actions without external guidance.>>
    That sounds liek a strange fabrication to me.  What is meant by
"unconscious"?  It seems to me this ignores the fact that all animals use
their senses to react to events they observe, and that affect them.  We have
a new cat these days (we used to own several, and just recenly resumed being
pet owners).  As I watch him, I certainly wouldn't say he's "unconsciious".
Unless this is equating "consciousness" with "capable of rational thought".
I feel the origin of religion is very obvious.  As man evolved and acquire
more and more intelligence, he developed a curiosity, a desire to
understand.  The forces of nature were beyond his understanding, and he
explained them by inventing gods.

    One of the new books I've just acqured is entititled "God Against the
Gods", and is a history of the development of monotheism.  I don't know if
you'd agree that monotheism is at least an improvement on polytheism.  My
attention to this question comes from reading a book "Who Wrote the Bible",
an excellent analysis of how the Old Testament came about.  In reviewing the
way the Jews relationship to Yahweh is described in the earlier period, I
came to realize that the belief was not true monotheism.  The Jews worshiped
Yahweh as THEIR only god, but did not particularly claim that the gods
worshipped by other peoples did not exist.  (It was "Yahweh is our guy;
other people have their own".)  In later stages, there is only a hint of a
feeling that the Jewish God is a universal one, but it doens't seem the
authors of the Old Testament ever made a big deal about it.

    It's interesting to carry this to the present day, because Christianity
can be accused of not being strictly monothesitic, with their Holy Trinity.
In fact, in reading the history of Islam, one of Mohammed's main points was
to advocate a strict monotheism ("There is only one God, and he is Allah")
in contrast to the Christians.  Early Muslims had less to quarrel with
theologically with the Jews than they did with the Christians, although they
didn't really think the Jews were emphatic enough in their monotheism.

